<div class="indented"><a id="comment-3289253"></a>


<div class="non_toggle_area" id="comment-3289253">
  <div class="non_toggle_label">
       <span class="scomments_info">Fri, 03/01/2013 - 02:36 | <a href="/news/2013-02-28/bitcoin-your-thoughts#comment-3289253" class="active">3289253</a></span>
              <b><a href="/users/silver-bully" title="View user profile.">Silver Bully</a></b>
  </div>

  <div class="comment-content">
    <div class="author"><div class="picture">
  <a href="/users/silver-bully" title="View user profile."><img src="/sites/all/themes/newsflash/images/bagicon.png" alt="Silver Bully&#039;s picture" title="Silver Bully&#039;s picture"  /></a></div>
</div><div class="author"></div>
    <p>'By inflation he means simply the increase of the money supply.'</p>
<p>Gold is constantly mined every year. There will be more gold next year than this year. And on and on. But it isn't inflationary because the RATE of increase remains constant, and the substance remains rare. Fiat money is inflationary because it can be produced in vast amounts, quickly, which will rapidly degrade the public's confidence in it.</p>
<p>Bitcoin works like gold - only so much can be 'mined' at one time. The hashing or mining process prevents any entity from suddenly creating untold amounts of BTC out of thin air. The rate it can be mined also gradually decreases over time as well. It is deflationary by design, not inflationary.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="links"></div>
</div>
<div class="indented"><a id="comment-3290909"></a>


<div class="non_toggle_area" id="comment-3290909">
